bug.short_desc: Illegal XML Schema - use=required and default

long_desc.thetext:
It is illegal in XML Schema for an attribute to both be declared with a default and and have use="required".
The following illegal XML Schema is produced by generating XML Schema in EMF using all the defaults from the wizard of reverse engineering an existing XML Schema and then generating the code: <xsd:attribute default="AbsoluteTerms" name="priceExpression" type="_2:PriceExpressionEnum" use="required"> <xsd:annotation> <xsd:documentation>Specifies whether the price is expressed in absolute or relative terms.</xsd:documentation> </xsd:annotation> </xsd:attribute>
The XML Schema this was reversed from had as its declaration: <xsd:element name="priceExpression" type="PriceExpressionEnum"> <xsd:annotation> <xsd:documentation xml:lang="en">Specifies whether the price is expressed in absolute or relative terms.</xsd:documentation> </xsd:annotation> </xsd:element>
Moving to XSD component.
A fix is committed to CVS. We'll generate an ecore:default in the case that a default is not permitted. The XSDEcoreBuilder will recognized that as well.

bug.short_desc: [Sync View] Empty folder not shown unless it is a source folder

long_desc.thetext:
When the source directory defined in build path is the root directory of project, modified directories are not detected.
To reproduce:
1) File > New > Project... 2) "Java Project" > Project Name: test
A new project "test" appears in package explorer. By default, the source dir is the project root.
3) Right click on "test" project > Team > Share... 4) Choose a valid CVS respository > Next > Next > Finish
Now the project is shared by CVS.
5) Right click on "(default package)" > New > Folder 6) Enter "a_dir" as folder name > Finish 7) Right click on "test" project > Compare With > Latest from HEAD
Result: The new dir "a_dir" is not in list of change
Expected: The dir "a_dir" should appears in list of change with [+] icon
If you change the source path to "a_dir", the new dir is detected. Thus this bug appears only when project root is source root.

bug.short_desc: [hashcode/equals] Support using superclass fields and methods (getters)

long_desc.thetext:
When using hibernate I want to have equals and hashCode methods in my POJOs for my database tables. We use the generation gap pattern for these classes so we have BasePerson (which is generated by hibernate tools and just contains the fields from the database and we have Person which extends BasePerson and contains our hand written code for persons.
We want our equals and hashCode methods to be in the Person class (not in the BasePerson) so we don't need to regenerate this methods each time we regenerate the BasePerson class.
The equals and hashCode methods generated with eclipce 3.2 don't have an option to use methods instead of variables (getName() vs name) so we can't move the equals and hashCode methods we generate in BasePerson to Person.
A solution to this issue could be to add an option in the generate hashcode and equals methods to specify if you want to use variables or methods.
Another solution to this issue could be to add an option for looking in the superclass for fields to include in the hashcode and equals method.
[not Mac specific; setting HW/OS to All)

One could argue that 'super.hashCode()' is sufficient for that. But offering the (visible) fields from the super class makes sense.
The wish to also offer methods has also already been brought up. I'm not yet convinced, but maybe we can just offer a filter for methods (with no arguments) and super fields. super.hashCode() could also be shown as a node to check or uncheck.

There is another situation when it would be useful to call the getters instead of using direct field access. When using Hibernate, the field in the generated proxy may be null, but calling the getter will still return the correct (non-null) value
(In reply to comment #2) > One could argue that 'super.hashCode()' is sufficient for that. But offering > the (visible) fields from the super class makes sense. > > The wish to also offer methods has also already been brought up. I'm not yet > convinced, but maybe we can just offer a filter for methods (with no arguments) > and super fields. > super.hashCode() could also be shown as a node to check or uncheck. >
*** Bug 164596 has been marked as a duplicate of this bug. ***
Extending this request to methods (getters).

> I'm not sure it makes sense for a subclass to use the superclass' fields > for computing equality[...]
There will always be someone who eventually needs it. As long as it's not dangerous to do it, you should allow it.
> What would happen in the case of exceptions being thrown[...]?
Getters must not throw checked exceptions. It's in the contract, so we're safe here.
And since equals() cannot handle the runtime exceptions (what should it do with them?), it must not catch them.

You'd have to take into account what would happen, though. Strictly, JavaBeans properties have to be public too -- but that doesn't mean you shouldn't consider get() methods that are protected (or friendly, or even private) for this method.
Note that section 7.3 of the JavaBeans specification explicitly allows for JavaBean Properties accessor methods to throw exceptions:
http://sdlc-esd.sun.com/ESD4/JSCDL/javabeans/1.01/beans.101.pdf?AuthParam=1163689822_24a0fee18bb77f3f6aad51ce908da115&TUrl=an1npDpbKod7kSYrROhENTonIeQ2W0D1Lc4nXz+pGFFranixdCdgxDTPbW4=&TicketId=dll9PwBJNOk4/w==&GroupName=SDLC&BHost=sdlc5i.sun.com&FilePath=/ESD4/JSCDL/javabeans/1.01/beans.101.pdf&File=beans.101.pdf
"7.3 Exceptions on accessor methods Both simple and indexed property accessor methods may throw checked exceptions. This allows property setter/getter methods to report exceptional conditions. Thus for example you might have: void setWombat(Wombat value) throws BadWombatException; Marsupial getKangaroo(int index) throws AwfulCommunicationException; "
Otherwise, you'd end up in a potential scenario where generation of a method that called a getter that threw an exception would result in a compilation error.
You could, of course, only show accessible getter methods that don't throw exceptions, thus sidestepping the issue.
PS The code that catches and re-throws the runtime exception is to stop the RuntimeException being swallowed by wrapping it around another RuntimeException. It's fairly standard practice to have a 'catch everything except' type block, and also keeps the stacktrace and line numbers visible to any callers who are handling it. It's unnecessary if you're not also catching generic Exceptions.
PPS Strictly speaking, a JavaBeans property need not start with get(), either. If a BeanInfo class is provided, you can set up mappings to link non-standard method names with property accessors. java.beans.Introspector.getBeanInfo(clazz) will return a BeanInfo object that contains all the properties for that class. If none are provided, it will instantiate a BeanInfo that uses the standard method names of get/set and the special-case is. I would suggest that if doing this approach, using the union of any visible 'get' methods and the readable properties of the resultant BeanInfo are used to present the list of options to the user.

bug.short_desc: UMLUtil.setBaseElement(EObject stereotypeApplication, Element element) should throw exception if no structural feature can be found for Stereotype with Extension.METACLASS_ROLE_PREFIX

long_desc.thetext:
When applying a Stereotype to a metaclass, if the Stereotype does not have a structural attribute, whose name starts with the Extension.METACLASS_ROLE_PREFIX, then the Stereotype is not applied, and the caller does not get any feedback about this. I would propose to raise an exception in this case, because in this case the profile does not seem to be valid.
It may additionally also be an option to included such a check in the validation checks for the Profile, so the user gets notified about such a problem.

I think that perhaps a check for the prefix should instead be made in ElementOperations#getExtension(Element, Stereotype) - this way, the stereotype will not be considered applicable if the prefix is missing. Does this work for you?

Yes, that would be perfectly fine with me.
The reason for issuing this request was that I created a profile, where I named all my stereotypes' properties with the prefix "base" instead of "base_" (I did not know there exists such a naming convention - maybe one can add a comment to the introduction to profiles article also) and I was able to apply these stereotypes in the UML editor, but they were indeed not applied. Just by debugging I noticed that there is a naming convention that I have to obey. If the stereotypes had not been applicable I would directly have searched for a problem in my profile. So your solution seems adequate.

The naming rules for extension ends are technically just conventions (see below), but in the absence of such a scheme, it becomes difficult to set the value for the right reference from the stereotype application to its base element (since there could be other properties that reference metaclass instances).
From the specification:
The role names are provided using the following rule: The name of the role of the extended metaclass is: base_extendedMetaclassName The name of the role of the extension stereotype is: extension_stereotypeName
Note that if you create your extensions using the Stereotype#createExtension(Class, boolean) method (as shown in the article) the extension ends (and their names) are set up automatically for you.
The fix has been committed to CVS.

bug.short_desc: getLastModified() for bundleentry URLConnections should correspond with Bundle.

long_desc.thetext:
Thes server-side work uses the URLConnections's getLastModified() to support caching. "bundleentry" URLs are currently using their underlying file or zip entries setting. I suspect they should instead be using the value returned from Bundle.getLastModified() as this describes when the URL was last changed.
I'm happy to do the fix here; just want to validate this first.
Simon, are you saying that if you update an entry in a zip file the timestamp of the zip entry does not get updated? Can you explain in more detail why the current behavior does not work? Thanks.

Hi Tom, The use-case I'm thinking about is when someone does a bundle.update with an older version of a bundle. In that case the underlying zip entries will be older but when translated to a bundleentry URLs the contents were last modified when the bundle was updated. Make sense?

This type of change would break other caching scenarios where we really do want to know the timestamp of the individual bundle entry, not the timestamp of the whole bundle. For example, the extension registry calculates timestamps based on this in case you change the plugin.xml file in a project in your workspace.

Yes, I wondered about that exact case. Maybe we should be resolving to a File URL first?? The plugin.xml case is a bit special as it's there to support a dev-time use-case. (er... I think, correct me if I'm wrong)
Are there a lot of other examples?
--
To support caching (without holding state) I ultimately just need the modified dates to increase monotonically. There maybe other approaches I can start to look at if this is a can of worms.

After thinking further about this -- downgrading to an enhancement request. (Tom if you want to mark INVALID or WONTFIX that's ok too)
There's nothing in the OSGi spec (at least currently) to suggest that URLs returned from bundle entries should have the getLastModified() semantics of the bundle. It should be perfectly valid to use any underlying URL scheme.

Simon, you may want to add a request to the public osgi bugzilla if you want an addition to the OSGi spec. (http://bundles.osgi.org/bugzilla/)
Closing as wontfix. Too many unknowns with such a change.

I can handle my caching in another way.

To duplicate a BundleDescription object. This method does not allow you to pass the exececution environment from the original BundleDescription. Bug 154105 means that we don't have a good way to make sure the execution environment does not get lost.
If that bug is not addressed for 3.2.1, then the best way we have to fix things on this side would be to duplicate the BundleDescription we have and then use reflection to get the setter method so that we can change the version from .qualifier.

bug.short_desc: Open Declaration should be hierarchy aware

long_desc.thetext:
I find myself looking through code, and I will Ctrl-click on a method that I want to go visit. But it's an interface or an abstract class, so I just get taken to a declaration that does nothing.

Same thing for abstract class, except that the abstract class' implementation would be one of the classes presented as a destination to visit.
Of course, I can highlight the method and do Search->Declarations, but the problem is that I don't know beforehand that I need to do that. I just want to Ctrl-click on a method and visit that method. And if it's an interface or abstract class, show me a list of possible destinations to pick from.
You can use Ctrl+T to navigate inside the hierarchy.

bug.short_desc: Installable runtime should support extraction of tar.gz archives

long_desc.thetext: The installable runtime support currently assumes a zipinputstream. The support should be enhanced to allow extraction of unix archives tar.gz files.

Agreed. This isn't as easy as using the GZip input stream instead, is it?
I don't suppose you'd have any time to devote to this? :)

Yes, you can assign this to me. I think that using GZip input stream along with apache's TarInputStream and TarEntry (which WTP i think includes) will do the trick, so the extraction code may vary slightly.

Did a little more investigation. The code is fairly simple, with the following caveats:
* It would probably use the path extension to tell if the file is a zip or tar, barring any other clean methods.
* The only place I could find a tar utility was in org.eclipse.ui.ide, which wst.server.core can't depend on. Either we need to find another copy, or copy TarEntry and TarInputStream (or equivalent) into wst.server.core. Copying would be ok short term, but I'm not sure I want to maintain a tar utility in server tools. We'd also have to double-check for potential licensing issues.
Is Geronimo waiting to use this and should I investigate the licensing and utility issues, or is this not a priority for WTP 2.0?

I would say this is a more nice to have, then a critical request. Downloading a .tar simply allows on unix platforms for the permissions on scripts to be preserved so that the server can be used manually outside of WTP. Since Geronimo isn't calling scripts to start the server, its doesn't affect the WTP integration.
If Eclipse can push the tar utility into a non-ui plugin, then it would be trivial work to get it working, otherwise I wouldn't lose sleep over it and we can lower the priority.
